In a #small pot{}, combine @Jasmine Rice{1/2%cup}, 3/4 cup water, and a pinch of @salt{}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}. Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

> 4 SERVINGS: Use 1 1/2 cups water.

While rice cooks, wash and dry all produce.

Quarter @Lime{1}.

In a #large bowl{}, combine @Mayonnaise{2%tablespoon}, half the @Chili Powder{1%teaspoon} (you'll use the rest later), and juice from half the lime. Season with @salt{} and @Pepper{}.

Drain @Corn{13.4%ounce}, then pat very dry with #paper towels{}.

Heat a drizzle of @Vegetable Oil{1%teaspoon} in a #large pan{} over high heat (if using a #nonstick pan{}, heat without oil). Add corn and cook, stirring occasionally, until golden brown and lightly charred in spots, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Turn off heat; transfer corn to bowl with chili mayo. Cover to keep warm. Wipe out #pan{}.

> TIP: If corn begins to pop, cover pan.

Heat another drizzle of @Vegetable Oil{1%teaspoon} in same pan over medium-high heat. Add @Ground Pork{10%ounce}, @Southwest Spice Blend{1%tablespoon}, remaining chili powder, and a big pinch of salt. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until pork is browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Stir in @Beef Stock Concentrate{1} and 1/4 cup water. Bring to a simmer and cook until saucy, ~{2-3%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper. Remove pan from heat.

> 4 SERVINGS: Use 1/3 cup water.

While pork cooks, stir half the @Monterey Jack Cheese{1/4%cup} (save the rest for serving) into bowl with corn mixture. Taste and season with salt, pepper, and another squeeze of lime juice if desired.

Fluff rice with a fork and season with salt and pepper.

Divide rice between #bowls{} and top with pork, esquites, and remaining Monterey Jack. Dollop with @Sour Cream{4%tablespoon} and drizzle with @Hot Sauce{1%teaspoon} to taste. Pick @Cilantro{1/4%ounce} leaves from stems; tear leaves into pieces and sprinkle over dish. Serve with any remaining lime wedges on the side.